"title":"Hemolytic Anemia",
"jsonContent":{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_hm_s13",
"title":{
"__html":"Hemolytic Anemia"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"3f9e93",
"children":[
"Hemolytic Anemia"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_hm_s13_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b5f763",
"children":[
"Characteristic findings are anemia, splenomegaly, elevated reticulocyte count, elevated ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"lactate dehydrogenase",
"children":[
"LDH"
]
},
" and indirect bilirubin, decreased haptoglobin, and elevated ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"mean corpuscular volume",
"children":[
"MCV"
]
},
" (caused by reticulocytosis)."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"80f307",
"children":[
"Hemolytic anemia can be either congenital or acquired."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"1308ef",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Congenital hemolytic anemias"
]
},
" include hemoglobinopathies (sickle cell disease), disorders of the erythrocyte membrane (hereditary spherocytosis), enzyme defects (",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase",
"children":[
"G6PD"
]
},
" deficiency), and thalassemia syndromes."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"c7f28d",
"children":[
"In ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"acquired hemolytic anemia,"
]
},
" hemolysis can occur secondary to medications (fludarabine, bendamustine, quinine, penicillins, Î±-methyldopa); can be immune in nature; or can occur secondary to micro- or macroangiopathic processes, infections, or physical agents."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"1e67f0",
"children":[
"Examining the peripheral blood smear is central to identifying erythrocyte morphologies that implicate certain hemolytic mechanisms."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_hm_s13_inline_t1",
"mk19_bb_hm_s13_inline_t2"
],
"forceOpen":true
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_hm_s13_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"4d849d",
"children":[
"All patients with sickle cell anemia or other hemolytic anemias require pneumococcal (both 23- and 13-valent), ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Haemophilus influenzae"
]
},
" type B, influenza, and meningococcal vaccinations."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"fdfdaa",
"children":[
"All patients with chronic hemolytic anemia require folic acid supplements."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"c1ea86",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Severe symptomatic autoimmune anemia:"
]
},
" transfusion even if fully matched erythrocytes are not available."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b2c2b3",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Warm autoimmune hemolytic anemia:"
]
},
" initial therapy is glucocorticoids."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b55ff1",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Cold agglutinin disease:"
]
},
" primary therapy is cold avoidance or rituximab for persistent symptoms; glucocorticoids or splenectomy are usually ineffective."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"42ea28",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"TTP"
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
":"
]
},
" emergent plasma exchange."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"873191",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Hereditary spherocytosis and transfusion-dependent thalassemias:"
]
},
" splenectomy."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"c818f2",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Severe thalassemia:"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"hematopoietic stem cell transplantation",
"children":[
"HSCT"
]
},
" is standard therapy."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"42f709",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Severe "
]
},
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"PNH"
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
":"
]
},
" eculizumab or ravulizumab."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"23e386",
"children":[
"A personal or family history of anemia, jaundice, splenomegaly, or gallstones suggests hereditary spherocytosis."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_hm_s13_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"d7893d",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A previously healthy 28-year-old woman with a negative family history has weakness and a palpable spleen. Hemoglobin concentration is 7.2 g/dL and the reticulocyte count is 9.8% of erythrocytes. Peripheral blood smear shows an occasional spherocyte."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f44fb0",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"direct antiglobulin test",
"children":[
"DAT"
]
},
" to establish diagnosis of autoimmune hemolytic anemia. For management, select glucocorticoids."
]
}
]
}
]
},
